Sea Dragon, had an LEO capacity of 1,200,000 pounds.<br>
You want to uprate the design to place 5,000,000 pounds<br>
into orbit?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 You misunderstand me. I was thinking of the 20 meter HLV lifted Orion ship (for &quot;post Saturn booster&quot;). Follow along: the Saturn-V model lifted the 500+ton ship to high altitude, where the NPR drive took over. Thus, the Saturn-V booster put 500 tons into LEO.<br>
 I guestimated the mass of the 20 meter Orion ship as ~2500 tons.<br>
<br>
 (I did recently put a picture of the 20 meter ship in the &quot;nuclear preserve&quot; No solid idea of the mass)<br>
<br>
 Should we speculate on carrying the design philosophy of the BDB further? Truax reasoned that the scale of the booster doesn't directly drive the cost up. Could a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> really big</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> HLV be built? Nah. I don't know and don't see that it's worth bending my brain around it. If you want more than a Sea Dragon in one shot, build a few hundred neutron bombs for an Orion...<br>
